/PG144/XX/PR

How precious is your love, O God,/PR

when earthborn find the shelter of your wing!/PR

Theyòre nourished from the riches of your house./PR

Give drink to them from your Edenic stream./PR

For with you is the fountain of all life,/PR

in your Light do we behold all light./PR

Extend your love to those who know you,/PR

and your justice to those honest in their hearts.    (Psalm 36:8-11)/PR

/SCD/XXERASH/XX. The tallit is a "garment of brightness." It links us with the whole
universe, with the whole of Nature. The blue thread within it (Numbers
15:37-41) reminds us that heaven and earth can touch, that the elements
of our universe are all wondrously connected.    /SC/XXL.B./XX/PR

/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. The wearing of the tallit has its origins in the biblical com-
mandment (Numbers 15:37-41) that a fringe should be attached to each
corner of a garment to remind the Israelites of the mitzvot. This garment,
resembling a poncho, was the basic garment worn every day. When cloth-
ing without such defined corners came to be customary, the tallit became
a special ritual garment. In our time, a large tallit is worn only during the
morning prayer, while traditional Jews wear a small tallit, also known as
/ITarba kanfot/XX / four corners, underneath their outer clothes. In the biblical
commandment the fringe was a color called  / /ITteh/±elet/XX, a particular
shade of purple-blue. When this was no longer available, the rabbis ruled
that the fringes should be an undyed white. Some contemporary Jews have
reinstituted the inclusion of blue in the fringe. Today in Reconstructionist
congregations, women are encouraged to wear tallitot as well./PR

/SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

